# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: college-of-justice
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] This **list of monastic houses in Scotland** is a catalogue of the abbeys, priories, friaries and other monastic religious houses of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] In this article alien houses are included, as are smaller establishments such as cells and notable monastic granges (particularly those with resident monks).
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The numerous monastic hospitals *per se* are not included here unless at some time the foundation had, or was purported to have, the status or function of an abbey, priory, friary or preceptory/commandery.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The geographical co-ordinates provided are sourced from details provided by the Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments in Scotland (RCAHMS) and Ordnance Survey publications.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] The list is presented alphabetically by council area.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Foundations are listed alphabetically within each area.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Locations with names in *italics* indicate probable duplication (misidentification with another location) or non-existent foundations (either erroneous reference or proposed foundation never implemented.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Communities/provenance: shows the status and communities existing at each establishment, together with such dates as having been established as well as the fate of the establishment after dissolution, and the current status of the site.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Formal name or dedication: shows the formal name of the establishment or the person in whose name the church is dedicated, where known.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] Alternative names: some of the establishments have had alternative names over the course of time.
[src:college-of-justice/abbeys-and-priories-in-scotland-p01] In order to assist in text-searching, such alternatives in name or spelling have been provided.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi unsuccessfully appealed his 2001 conviction.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In June 2007, the Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission granted Megrahi leave to appeal his Lockerbie bombing conviction for a second time.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi abandoned his second appeal in August 2009 as an ongoing appeal would have prevented him from being moved to Libya under the Prisoner Transfer Scheme which was thought to be a possibility.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] He decided to drop his appeal two days before he was released on compassionate grounds by the Scottish Government on 20 August 2009.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Doctors had reported on 10 August 2009 that he had terminal prostate cancer.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On his return to Libya, al-Megrahi was hospitalized, then allowed to leave on 2 November 2009, taking up residence in a villa in Tripoli.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] He died on 20 May 2012, 33 months after his release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] An ethnic Magarha, Abdelbaset al-Megrahi was born in Tripoli on 1 April 1952 to a poor family.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Although little is known of his early life, in 1971, he spent nine months studying in Cardiff, Wales and in the late 1970s, he made multiple visits to the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Later, he was the head of security for Libyan Arab Airlines (LAA), and director of the Centre for Strategic Studies in Tripoli.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] It was alleged by the FBI and the prosecution in the Lockerbie case that he was also an officer of the Libyan intelligence service, Mukhabarat el-Jamahiriya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In November 1991, Megrahi and Fhimah were indicted by the US Attorney General and the Scottish Lord Advocate for the bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Libya refused to extradite the two accused, but held them under armed house arrest in Tripoli, offering to detain them for trial in Libya, as long as all the incriminating evidence was provided.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The offer was unacceptable to the US and UK, and there was an impasse for the next three years.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 23 March 1995, over six years after the 1988 attack, Megrahi and Fhimah were designated as United States fugitives from justice and became the 441st and 442nd additions on the FBI Ten Most Wanted Fugitives list.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] This list offered a US$4 million reward from the US Air Line Pilots Association, Air Transport Association, and United States Department of State, and $50,000 from the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI), for information leading to their arrest.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The parties eventually agreed on a compromise and a trial was held in the Netherlands under Scots law.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The trial format was engineered by legal academic Professor Robert Black of the University of Edinburgh and was given political impetus by the British foreign secretary, Robin Cook.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Protracted negotiations with the Libyan leader, Colonel Muammar Gaddafi, and the imposition of UN economic sanctions against Libya brought the two accused to trial in a neutral country.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Over ten years after the bombing, Megrahi and Fhimah were placed under arrest at Camp Zeist in the Netherlands on 5 April 1999.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] During his seven-year house arrest awaiting deportation and trial, Megrahi lived on a Libyan Arab Airlines pension and worked as a teacher.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Scottish High Court of Justiciary at Camp Zeist was presided over by three senior judges and an additional, non-voting, judge.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The two accused, Megrahi and Lamin Khalifah Fhimah, denied all charges against them.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The full charges included the names of the murdered 259 passengers and crew of Pan Am Flight 103, and the eleven residents killed on the ground at Lockerbie in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Representing Megrahi were his solicitor, Alistair Duff, and advocates William Taylor KC, David Burns KC and John Beckett.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Fhimah was represented by solicitor Eddie McKechnie and advocates Richard Keen QC, Jack Davidson QC and Murdo MacLeod.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Both defendants also had access to a Libyan defence lawyer, Kamel Maghur, a former foreign affairs minister in the Libyan government.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Court proceedings started on 3 May 2000.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The crucial witness against Megrahi for the prosecution was Tony Gauci, a Maltese storekeeper, who testified that he had sold Megrahi the clothing later found in the remains of the suitcase bomb.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] At the trial, Gauci appeared uncertain about the exact date he sold the clothes in question, and was not entirely sure that it was Megrahi to whom they were sold.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Nonetheless, Megrahi's appeal against conviction was rejected by the Scottish Court in the Netherlands in March 2002.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Five years after the trial, former Lord Advocate, Lord Fraser of Carmyllie, publicly described Gauci as being "an apple short of a picnic" and "not quite the full shilling".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] During the trial, the defence showed that Megrahi's co-defendant, Fhimah, had a watertight alibi, having been in Sweden at the time of the sabotage.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The judges announced their verdict on 31 January 2001.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The judges unanimously found the second accused, Lamin Khalifah Fhimah, not guilty of the murder charge.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Fhimah was freed and returned to his home at Souk al-Juma in Libya on 1 February 2001.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi was sent to Barlinnie Prison in Scotland to serve his sentence.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In February 2005, he was transferred to HM Prison Greenock.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi's appeal against his conviction in January 2001 was refused on 14 March 2002 by a panel of five Scottish judges at Camp Zeist in the Netherlands.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] According to a report by the BBC, Dr Hans Köchler, one of the UN observers at the trial, expressed serious doubts about the fairness of the proceedings and spoke of a "spectacular miscarriage of justice".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] This court hearing was the result of the incorporation into Scots law of the European Convention on Human Rights in 2001, nine months after Megrahi's sentence was imposed, which required him to be told the extent of the "punishment part" of his life term.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 31 May 2004, he was granted leave to appeal against his 27-year sentence.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The appeal against sentence was scheduled to be heard in Edinburgh by a panel of five Judges on 11 July 2006.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] However, the Scottish Court of Criminal Appeal decided to postpone the July hearing to allow consideration of whether the appeal against sentence ought to be heard at Camp Zeist rather than in Edinburgh.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 23 September 2003, lawyers acting for Megrahi applied to the Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission (SCCRC) for a review of the case (both sentence and conviction), arguing that there had been a miscarriage of justice.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 1 November 2006, Megrahi was reported to have dropped his demand for the new appeal to be held at Camp Zeist.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In January 2007, the SCCRC announced that it would issue its decision on Megrahi's case by the end of June 2007.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 9 June 2007, rumours of a possible prisoner swap deal involving Megrahi were strenuously denied by the then-prime minister, Tony Blair.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 28 June 2007, the SCCRC concluded its four-year review and, having uncovered evidence that a miscarriage of justice could have occurred, the commission granted Megrahi leave to appeal against his Lockerbie bombing conviction for a second time.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The second appeal to the Court of Criminal Appeal was abandoned in August 2009, as an impediment to the legal power to release him to Libya under the Prisoner Transfer Scheme then operating in the United Kingdom.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Ultimately, he was not released under this scheme but rather on compassionate grounds due to his ill health.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] There was in any event no requirement to drop his appeal against conviction.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Tony Gauci, chief prosecution witness at the trial, was alleged to have been paid $2 million for testifying against Megrahi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Mebo's owner, Edwin Bollier, claimed that in 1991 the FBI offered him $4 million to testify that the timer fragment found near the scene of the crash was part of a Mebo MST-13 timer supplied to Libya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Former employee of Mebo Ulrich Lumpert swore an affidavit in July 2007 that he had stolen a prototype MST-13 timer in 1989, and had handed it over to "a person officially investigating the Lockerbie case".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 1 November 2007, Megrahi invited Professor Robert Black QC to visit him at Greenock Prison.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] After a two-hour meeting, Black stated "that not only was there a wrongful conviction, but the victim of it was an innocent man.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Prior to Megrahi's second appeal, another four procedural hearings took place at the High Court of Appeal in Edinburgh between December 2007 and June 2008.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In the June 2008 edition of the Scottish lawyers' magazine *The Firm*, the UN Observer at the Lockerbie trial, Professor Hans Köchler, referred to the 'totalitarian' nature of Megrahi's second appeal process saying it "bears the hallmarks of an 'intelligence operation'".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 15 October 2008, five Scottish judges decided unanimously to reject a submission by the Crown Office to the effect that the scope of Megrahi's second appeal should be limited to the specific grounds of appeal that were identified by the SCCRC in June 2007.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In January 2009, it was reported that, although Megrahi's second appeal against conviction was scheduled to begin on 27 April 2009, the hearing could last as long as 12 months because of the complexity of the case and volume of material to be examined.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Scottish ministers denied in April 2009 they had clandestinely agreed to the repatriation of Megrahi before the start of his second appeal on 28 April.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Kenny MacAskill announced in May 2011 that the re-elected SNP Government would seek to change Scots law to allow publication of the SCCRC report, which can presently be blocked by any party that provided evidence to the review.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Nevertheless, *The Herald* published this report online in March 2012.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The first Scottish call for the release of Megrahi was made by Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland Iain Torrance.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] At the beginning of 2003, Nelson Mandela had asked for the intervention of the Western Christian churches in what he described as "a clear miscarriage of justice".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] This led to the production of a highly critical report of the scientific and forensic evidence presented at the original trial by the Church of Scotland's leading scientist Dr John Urquhart Cameron.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] As a result, in July 2003, Torrance petitioned the then prime minister Tony Blair to consider his release in view of the widespread unease in Scotland concerning the safety of the verdict.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 14 September 2008, the Arab League Ministerial Council passed a resolution calling for the 'political hostage' Megrahi to be released from prison in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The resolution demanded that the Scottish government should hand to Megrahi's lawyers the documents which the SCCRC had identified, adding that Britain's refusal to do so represented a 'miscarriage of justice'.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Arab League also endorsed Libya's right to compensation for the damage done to its economy by UN sanctions which were in force from 1991 until 1999.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 6 November 2008, three Criminal Appeal Court judges reserved judgment on an application by defence counsel Maggie Scott for Megrahi to be released on bail pending his second appeal against conviction which was expected to be heard in 2009.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] A week later, Megrahi's bail application was refused.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 14 August 2009, Megrahi withdrew his appeal.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] South of Scotland SNP MSP Christine Grahame said, "There are a number of vested interests who have been deeply opposed to this appeal continuing as they know it would go a considerable way towards exposing the truth behind Lockerbie...
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Dalyell was supported by Nelson Mandela, the Church of Scotland, the Catholic Church, the law faculties of the Scottish universities, the representatives of British relatives and the UN's official observer at the trial in The Hague.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Alistair Darling, the UK Chancellor of the Exchequer from 2007 to 2010, stated that "It's true to say that the British Government wanted Megrahi out.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] It's probably true to say that [Scottish First Minister] Alex Salmond fancied a wander into the international stage" but denies that British government had anything to do with the release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] They had five children: four sons and one daughter.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 23 September 2008, Megrahi was diagnosed with advanced prostate cancer at age 56, prompting calls for his second appeal to be heard promptly.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 4 December 2008, Megrahi's family joined others protesting against alleged miscarriages of justice within the Scottish justice system.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] An online petition to the Scottish Ministers seeking Megrahi's compassionate release was raised on 19 December 2008.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] It stated that he was terminally ill and would benefit physically and psychologically from compassionate release to his temporary home in Glasgow while he awaited the outcome of the appeal granted to him by the Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission in June 2007.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Since it was likely to be months before such an appeal was finally decided, the petition asked that Megrahi be allowed to spend his "very limited" remaining time in Scotland with his family and loved ones.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 4 August 2009, the Cabinet Secretary for Justice in Scotland, Kenny MacAskill, visited Greenock Prison to hear Megrahi's request for a prisoner transfer to Libya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] MacAskill faced international pressure from politicians in the United Kingdom and United States, with U.S. victims' groups and Syracuse University (which lost 25 students in the Lockerbie bombing) all urging him not to release Megrahi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 14 August, lawyers representing Megrahi announced that he had applied to the High Court in Edinburgh two days previously to withdraw his second appeal, and that his condition had "taken a significant turn for the worse".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 19 August 2009, it was divulged that MacAskill had reached a decision on the bomber's fate to be announced the following day.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The following day, MacAskill granted his release on compassionate grounds, stating that Megrahi was in the final stages of terminal prostate cancer and was expected to die within three months.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Speaking of the Scottish tradition of justice with compassion and mercy, MacAskill said he was "bound by Scottish values to release him", and allow him to die in his home country of Libya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Immediately following the announcement, Megrahi, who had served just over 8+1⁄2 years of his life sentence, was escorted by Strathclyde Police to Glasgow Airport where he boarded a specially chartered aircraft to Tripoli operated by the Libyan state-owned Afriqiyah Airways.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The aircraft – an Airbus A300 (registration 5A-IAY) – was the personal aircraft of Colonel Gaddafi; it was destroyed on the ground at Tripoli Airport in 2011 during fighting to overthrow the Gaddafi regime.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi arrived back in time to join celebrations to mark 40 years since the country's revolution.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi landed in Libya to national celebrations and acclaim.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] As he left the plane, a crowd of several hundred young people were gathered at Tripoli Airport to welcome him, some waving Libyan or Scottish flags, others throwing flower petals.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Some had been ushered away by Libyan officials in an attempt to play down the arrival in accordance with British and US wishes.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi was accompanied by Saif al-Islam Gaddafi, son of Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, who had pledged in 2008 to bring al-Megrahi home, and was then joined on the aircraft steps by Lamin Khalifah Fhimah.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] This was the first time the pair had met since they had stood side by side during their eight-month trial at Camp Zeist, in the Netherlands 8 ½ years earlier.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] After he left the aircraft, Megrahi was driven away in convoy for a long-awaited meeting with his 86-year-old mother, Hajja Fatma Ali al-Arabi, who a few days earlier had pleaded emotionally with Scottish Ministers to release her son.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Hajja had not been told of her son's terminal cancer for fear that the shock would be too much for her.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi also met Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The reception was shown afterwards on Libyan state television.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In an interview the following day with *The Times*, Megrahi vowed to present new evidence before he died which would exonerate him of any involvement in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing: "If there is justice in the UK I would be acquitted or the verdict would be quashed because it was unsafe.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] There was a miscarriage of justice ... my message to the British and Scottish communities is that I will put out the evidence and ask them to be the jury".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Following his release, Megrahi was taken to Tripoli Medical Center, Libya's most advanced public clinic, for cancer treatment.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] A video of him in the hospital showed him using an oxygen mask to breathe.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 2 September 2009, it was reported that his cancer had worsened, and that he had been transferred to the intensive care unit (ICU).
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Libyan Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammed Seyala claimed that Megrahi had been moved to a special VIP wing of the hospital, was receiving full treatment from a team of doctors, and that his condition was not dangerous.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi's family claimed that they had been informed that he had been taken to the ICU, but they were not allowed to visit him.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Foreign Ministry confirmed that his family were not allowed to visit him, but said that it was to ensure his safety.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 5 September, Megrahi was released from the ICU, but remained under close observation by a team of doctors.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] While in hospital, Megrahi underwent chemotherapy treatment, receiving the drug docetaxel.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] He was discharged from hospital on 2 November, and sent to live with his family in the New Damascus district in west Tripoli, in a villa reportedly built or bought for him, shortly before his release, by the Libyan government.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Under police protection, he resumed chemotherapy, making regular visits to hospital for chemotherapy sessions and other intensive treatment.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Following the release, doubts were expressed whether Megrahi was as ill as claimed by MacAskill in his statement to the Scottish Parliament.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The guidance on compassionate release of a terminally ill prisoner under Scottish law specifies that death must be likely to occur "soon"; there is no fixed time limit but a life expectancy of three months is suggested as "appropriate".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Labour MSP for Mid Scotland and Fife and a Minister in the previous Labour administration, Dr Richard Simpson, accused the Scottish justice minister of failing to conduct sufficient checks before deciding to release Megrahi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 27 August 2009, *The Scotsman*, quoting an anonymous Scottish Government source, reported that MacAskill ignored the advice of four specialists who were unwilling to speculate on Megrahi's anticipated lifespan.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] However the prison doctors and some experts brought in had said that Megrahi met the Scottish standards for release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The release of prisoners on compassionate grounds is up to the Minister of Justice and not to a committee.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Soon afterwards, Libyan media reported that Megrahi was able to talk to his mother by telephone from his hospital bed and *The Times*, at the beginning of November, suggested that his condition had not deteriorated significantly.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In early April 2010 it was reported that his cancer was no longer responding to treatment.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Libyan Consul General in Glasgow also reported that his condition had rapidly deteriorated.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In July 2010, Dr Sikora told *The Daily Telegraph*, "There was always a chance he could live for 10 years, 20 years ... but that would be unusual".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In response to an attempt to have his medical condition made public from Scottish Conservatives in July 2010, First Minister Alex Salmond compared him to one of Britain's most famous prisoners, Ronald Biggs, who was outliving al-Megrahi while on compassionate release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In a July 2010 interview with Scottish Television Dr Sikora said that his statements were misquoted extensively by dropping his qualification that 10 years' survival "would be unusual".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] He stated that the chances of such a long survival would be less than 1% but there was a 90% likelihood that he would be dead in a matter of weeks.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] UPI was still reporting the other version in August 2010.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Libyan media outlets reported Megrahi had been released from the hospital and was living at his family's villa.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 26 July 2011, during the First Libyan Civil War, Megrahi was shown on Libyan state television, attending a pro-Gaddafi rally of members of his tribe.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Megrahi appeared to be frail, and was in a wheelchair.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] However, in late August 2011, CNN reported that a TV crew had found Megrahi comatose and, according to his family, on his deathbed.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Notwithstanding this report, in early October in an interview with Reuters from his bed, al-Megrahi protested his innocence and claimed that he had only days, weeks or months to live.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 29 August 2011, a letter written by Megrahi was discovered by *The Wall Street Journal* at intelligence headquarters in Tripoli, Libya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In what was a private letter to Libya's intelligence chief not previously available to the public, Megrahi wrote "I am an innocent man", a letter apparently composed while he was serving a life sentence in Scotland, and written in blue ink on ordinary paper.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The letter was found in a steel four-drawer filing cabinet that had been forced open by rebels who entered the office of intelligence chief Abdullah al-Senussi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Jim Swire, whose daughter Flora was killed in the bombing and who has been a spokesman for UK Families Flight 103, which represented British relatives, has said that he believes Megrahi is innocent.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Swire is also concerned by comments attributed to the former lord advocate Lord Fraser, which appeared to doubt the credibility of the key prosecution witness, Tony Gauci.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Swire said "the scandal around Megrahi is not that a sick man was released, but that he was ever convicted in the first place.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Professor Robert Black, an expert in Scots law who devised the non-jury trial that saw the Lockerbie case heard in 2000, has called Megrahi's murder conviction "the most disgraceful miscarriage of justice in Scotland for 100 years".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Professor Black said he felt "a measure of personal responsibility" for persuading Libya to allow Megrahi and his co-accused, Al-Amin Khalifa Fhima, who was acquitted, to stand trial under Scots law.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The non-profit religious think tank Ekklesia noted that "all of the Crown's witnesses in the 36-week trial, which took place at a specially convened Scottish Court in the Netherlands, have subsequently been discredited.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 28 August 2009, *The Herald* published an interview conducted with Colonel Gaddafi's son, Saif al-Islam Gaddafi, in which he stated that Megrahi's release was not tied to any oil deals but was an entirely separate issue.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Referring to the Prisoner Transfer Agreement (PTA), he continued, "People should not get angry because we were talking about commerce or oil.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The commerce and politics and deals were all with the PTA.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] This was one animal and the other was the compassionate release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 30 August, an article published in the *Sunday Times* claimed ministers at Westminster had agreed not to specifically exclude al-Megrahi from an agreement concerning prisoner transfers in 2007 because of "overwhelming national interests".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In a letter dated 19 December 2007, Secretary of State for Justice Jack Straw wrote to his Scottish counterpart, "I had previously accepted the importance of the al-Megrahi issue to Scotland and said I would try to get an exclusion for him on the face of the agreement.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] I have not been able to secure an explicit exclusion.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Straw denied that the release was part of any deal, while Scottish First Minister Alex Salmond reiterated that the release had been granted on compassionate grounds and not as part of any deal struck by the British Government.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 16 July 2010, four United States senators made public their concerns over the release, stating they believed that the oil company BP pushed for his release to secure a deal with Libya.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] BP confirmed that it did press for a Prisoner Transfer Agreement as it was aware that a delay might have "negative consequences" for UK commercial interests.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] However, the firm said it was not involved in any discussions regarding Megrahi's release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] While President Obama expressed surprise at the decision, stating "I think all of us here in the United States were surprised, disappointed and angry about the release", the U.S. government was aware that a release was possible.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 18 September 2009, Megrahi released a 300-page dossier of evidence that challenges the prosecution case against him, and that he believed would have secured his release on appeal.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The release of the evidence dossier was condemned by Lord Advocate Elish Angiolini, who said that Megrahi had abandoned his appeal before his release on compassionate grounds.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Another stated that the UK feared action by Libya against British interests if Megrahi died in jail.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] It also stated that the UK government fully supported his release by the Scottish government.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The United States urged the National Transitional Council (NTC) to review the case, with a view towards deporting Megrahi if he did not die in the meantime.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The Scottish government rejected the calls, saying that only it could make such a request, and that it would not do so, as Megrahi had abided by the conditions of his release.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] NTC leaders initially said that they would not deport Megrahi or any other Libyan, but also admitted that only the future elected government of Libya could deal with such issues.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Following the fall of Tripoli when forces of the NTC had largely taken control of Libya, there were calls for al-Megrahi to be extradited to the United States.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] These calls were dismissed by the Scottish government and the NTC in Libya until such time as a decision can be made by the new elected government.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The United States government has said that it has asked the new Libyan government to re-examine the Megrahi case.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 30 August 2011, the Scottish First Minister Alex Salmond said, "The latest pictures broadcast of Mr al-Megrahi clearly demonstrate that he is an extremely sick man, dying of terminal prostate cancer.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Hopefully, this will end the ridiculous conspiracy theories that seek to claim anything else." He also said that the issue was under Scottish jurisdiction and that what American lawyers and senators had to say "was neither here nor there".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In October 2011, Al-Megrahi gave an interview from his bed in which he claimed that he had only days, weeks or months to live.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] After the killing of Muammar Gaddafi on 20 October 2011, the United States Secretary of State Hillary Clinton called for al-Megrahi to be returned to prison in Scotland, describing the release of al-Megrahi as a miscarriage of justice.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Additionally Clinton stated that having already raised the question of al-Megrahi's return to a Scottish prison with the leadership of the NTC, she would raise the matter again once a Libyan government had been formed.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Clinton also indicated that, while preferring imprisonment in Scotland, she supported imprisonment outside Scotland over al-Megrahi remaining out of jail.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] State Department indicated that it was preparing to make a "formal approach" to the NTC, requesting al-Megrahi's extradition to the United States.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Al-Megrahi died at home in Tripoli on 20 May 2012 at the age of 60.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] His funeral was held the following day, on 21 May.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] British Prime Minister David Cameron, speaking at a NATO summit in Chicago, said that it was a day to think of the victims of "an appalling terrorist act".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Scottish First Minister Alex Salmond also stated that people should use the occasion of al-Megrahi's death to remember the Lockerbie victims.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] *The Guardian* reported that Libyans "expressed relief rather than sadness" at news of al-Megrahi's death, as he was a reminder of the international sanctions that had impoverished the country following the bombing.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Many families of the Lockerbie victims called for al-Megrahi's appeal to be reopened following his death and headed by investigators outside Scotland, claiming that it would exonerate al-Megrahi.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Alex Salmond said it was up to Megrahi's relatives to apply to the Scottish Criminal Case Review Commission to seek a further appeal, adding that his death "ends one chapter of the Lockerbie case, but it does not close the book".
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In May 2014, a group of relatives of the Lockerbie victims continued to campaign for al-Megrahi's name to be cleared by reopening the case.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] On 5 June 2014, it was announced that Glasgow-based lawyer, Aamer Anwar, was instructed by immediate members of Al-Megrahi's family.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Although Al-Megrahi had died from cancer following his compassionate release from prison an application was still being lodged with the Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission seeking to review his case and return it to the appeal court as a miscarriage of justice.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] Aamer Anwar was also instructed by 24 British relatives of passengers who died on the flight, including Dr Jim Swire.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In December 2014, Frank Mulholland, the Lord Advocate (Scotland's senior law officer), restated his belief that al-Megrahi had been guilty of the bombing and that he was hopeful that progress might be made in the continuing investigation to find al-Megrahi's accomplices.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In December 2018 Eddie Fenech Adami, Malta's Prime Minister at the time of the bombing, said "we have never accepted the theory" of how Abdul Baset Ali al-Megrahi transported the bomb from Malta to the UK and suggested that a miscarriage of justice had taken place.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In January 2021, the Scottish Court of Criminal Appeal rejected both the contention that a miscarriage of justice may have occurred over the non-disclosure of secret documents and also that a possibly unreasonable verdict had been arrived at.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] In contrast, the Scottish judges ruled that incriminating evidence concerning luggage tags, which had originally been deemed inadmissible, should have been ruled admissible at the original trial.
[src:college-of-justice/abdelbaset-al-megrahi] The court found that the inclusion of this evidence made the case against al-Megrahi and his co-accused, Lamin Khalifah Fhimah, substantially stronger.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:college-of-justice/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] An **Act of Adjournal** is secondary legislation made by the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts hearing criminal matters.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] Now primarily derived from the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, the original power to create Acts of Adjournal is derived from an Act of the Parliament of Scotland in 1672.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] Before promulgation, Acts of Adjournal are reviewed and may be commented upon by the Criminal Courts Rules Council.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Adjournal are made as Scottish Statutory Instruments.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] Before devolution, acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] 40) (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary by attaching five Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] The act provided that "the judges of that court [...] regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court," a provision which remains in force and which created the distinction between Acts of Adjournal and Acts of Sederunt.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] In the 19th century, a reforming of the High Court of Justiciary made all Lords of Session *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-adjournal] That reformation, while now repealed, is replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which further provides that the Lord President of the Court of Session is to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] An **Act of Sederunt** (/səˈdɛrənt/ *sə-DERR-ənt*; meaning a meeting or sitting of a court) is secondary legislation made by the Court of Session, the supreme civil court of Scotland, to regulate the proceedings of Scottish courts and tribunals hearing civil matters.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Originally made under an Act of the Parliament of Scotland of 1532, the modern power to make Acts of Sederunt is largely derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Since 2013, draft Acts have also been prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and submitted to the Court of Session for approval.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Following Scottish devolution and the establishment of the Scottish Parliament, Acts of Sederunt are made as Scottish statutory instruments.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Previously, Acts were made as United Kingdom statutory instruments, and before that were a separate class of legislation.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session—more accurately the College of Justice—was established by the Parliament of Scotland under James V in 1532.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The act of Parliament establishing the Court, later named the College of Justice Act 1532 (c.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Although established in 1532, it was not until the passing of the **College of Justice Act 1540** (March c.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] 10 (S)), also known as the Act of Sederunt 1540 (originally titled *Ratification of the institution of the college of justice*) that the Court of Session gained the power to make law through Acts of Sederunt.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act 1672 (originally *Act concerning the regulation of the judicatories*) created the High Court of Justiciary, the supreme criminal court of Scotland, by attaching five of the Lords of Session to the Lord Justice General and Lord Justice Clerk.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Courts Act also provided that "the judges of that court ... regulate the inferior officers thereof, and order every other thing concerning the said court", and so created the distinction between Acts of Sederunt and Acts of Adjournal which continues to exist to this day.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Following a 19th-century reforming of the High Court of Justiciary, all Lords of Session were *ex officio* Lords Commissioners of Justiciary, instead of the original five ordained by the Courts Act.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Although that reformation was repealed, its effect was replicated by the Criminal Procedure (Scotland) Act 1995, which provided that the Lord President of the Court of Session was also to hold the office of Lord Justice General.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The powers of the Court of Session to make Acts of Sederunt were partially consolidated by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, which also made significant changes to the structure and operations of the Court.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] One of these significant changes was the establishing of a Rules Council, composed of the Lord President as well as Court of Session judges and practising lawyers, to propose Acts of Sederunt to the Court.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Act also created a Sheriff Court Rules Council, to carry out the same functions but in relation to the sheriff courts.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Sheriff Courts (Scotland) Act 1971 enabled the Court of Session to regulate the sheriff courts and Sheriff Appeal Court when they heard civil matters.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Act also dissolved the Sheriff Court Rules Council created by the Administration of Justice (Scotland) Act 1933, and created a new Sheriff Court Rules Council to continually review sheriff court procedure and submit to the Court of Session draft Acts of Sederunt for regulating sheriff courts.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Act 1988 was another consolidating act, now with sections relating to Acts of Sederunt largely repealed or modified by the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014, that also altered the structure of the Court of Session.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The remaining powers to make Acts of Sederunt relate to summary trials—although the actual power is now derived from the Courts Reform (Scotland) Act 2014—and the considering of applications to appeal to the Inner House by a single judge.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session Rules Council and Sheriff Court Rules Council were dissolved by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013, which established the Scottish Civil Justice Council as their replacement.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include draft inquiry procedure rules.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Court of Session's power to create Acts of Sederunt was extended by the Inquiries into Fatal Accidents and Sudden Deaths etc.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] (Scotland) Act 2016 to include the power to regulate the practice and procedure of public inquiries and fatal accident inquiries.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] As with other secondary legislation, an Act of Sederunt can only make law within the scope set out by an enabling act—an item of primary legislation from which power to make secondary legislation is derived.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] A non-exhaustive summary of these powers is provided below.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] In exercising these powers, the Court of Session can amend or repeal any enactment, including primary legislation, if it relates to matters an Act of Sederunt may cover.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Note, however, that the power to regulate admission into the Faculty of Advocates is effectively delegated from the Court of Session to the Faculty, as the Court legislated to require that those seeking admission meet criteria set out by the Faculty.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of the Court of Session are developed by the Scottish Civil Justice Council, which was established by the Scottish Civil Justice Council and Criminal Legal Assistance Act 2013.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The Council prepares draft rules of procedure for the civil courts and advises the Lord President on the development of the civil justice system in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] The SCJC will consider changes to practice and procedure in response to policy initiatives, by specific request, or of its own accord.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Membership of the council is provided for in the 2013 Act.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Rules for the functioning of civil procedure in the sheriff courts are also prepared by the Scottish Civil Justice Council.
[src:college-of-justice/act-of-sederunt] Acts of Sederunt, like other legislation in the United Kingdom, are introduced by enacting formulae.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The **Acts of Union** refer to two acts of Parliament, one by the Parliament of Scotland in March 1707, followed shortly thereafter by an equivalent act of the Parliament of England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] They put into effect the international Treaty of Union agreed on 22 July 1706, which politically joined the Kingdom of England and Kingdom of Scotland into a single "political state" named Great Britain, with Queen Anne as its sovereign.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The English and Scottish acts of ratification took effect on 1 May 1707, creating the new kingdom, with its parliament based in the Palace of Westminster.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The two countries had shared a monarch since the "personal" Union of the Crowns in 1603, when James VI of Scotland inherited the English throne from his cousin Elizabeth I to become (in addition) 'James I of England', styled James VI and I.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Prior to 1603, England and Scotland had different monarchs, but when Elizabeth I died without children, she was succeeded as King of England by her distant relative, James VI of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] After her death, the two Crowns were held in personal union by James (reigning as James VI and I), who announced his intention to unite the two realms.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The 1603 Union of England and Scotland Act established a joint Commission to agree terms, but the Parliament of England was concerned this would lead to an absolutist structure similar to that of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] James was forced to withdraw his proposals, but used the royal prerogative to take the title "King of Great Britain".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Attempts to revive the project of union in 1610 were met with hostility.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] English opponents such as Sir Edwin Sandys argued that changing the name of England "were as yf [*sic*] to make a conquest of our name, which was more than ever the Dane or Norman could do".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, James set about creating a unified Church of Scotland and England, as the first step towards a centralised, Unionist state.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] However, despite both being nominally Episcopal in structure, the two were very different in doctrine; the Church of Scotland, or kirk, was Calvinist in doctrine, and viewed many Church of England practices as little better than Catholicism.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] As a result, attempts to impose religious policy by James and his son Charles I ultimately led to the 1639–1651 Wars of the Three Kingdoms.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The 1639–1640 Bishops' Wars confirmed the primacy of the Scots kirk, and established a Covenanter government in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scots remained neutral when the First English Civil War began in 1642, before becoming concerned at the impact on Scotland of an English Royalist victory.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Presbyterian leaders like Argyll viewed union as a way to ensure free trade between England and Scotland, and preserve a Scots Presbyterian kirk.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Under the 1643 Solemn League and Covenant, the Scots Parliament agreed to provide military support to its English counterpart in return for a united Presbyterian church, but did not explicitly commit to political union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] As the war progressed, Scots and English Presbyterians increasingly viewed the English Independents, and associated radical groups like the Levellers, as a bigger threat than the Royalists.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Both Royalists and Presbyterians agreed monarchy was divinely ordered, but disagreed on the nature and extent of Royal authority over the church.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] When Charles I surrendered in 1646, an English pro-Royalist faction known as the Engagers allied with their former enemies to restore him to the English throne.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] After defeat in the 1647–1648 Second English Civil War, Scotland was occupied by English troops, which were withdrawn once those whom Cromwell held responsible had been replaced by the Kirk Party.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In December 1648, Pride's Purge paved the way for the Trial of Charles I in England by excluding MPs who opposed it.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Following the execution of Charles I in January 1649, and establishment of the Commonwealth of England, the Scots Kirk Party proclaimed Charles II King of Scots and England and, in the 1650 Treaty of Breda, resolved to restore him to the English throne.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Instead, defeat in the Anglo-Scottish War resulted in Scotland's incorporation into the Commonwealth in 1653, largely driven by Cromwell's determination to break the power of the Scots kirk.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The 1652 Tender of Union was followed on 12 April 1654 by *An Ordinance by the Protector for the Union of England and Scotland,* creating the Commonwealth of England and Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It was ratified by the Second Protectorate Parliament on 26 June 1657, creating a single Parliament in Westminster, with 30 representatives each from Scotland and Ireland added to the existing English members.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] While integration into the Commonwealth established free trade between Scotland and England, the economic benefits were diminished by the costs of military occupation.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Both Scotland and England associated union with heavy taxes and military rule; it had little popular support in either Country, and the union was dissolved after the Restoration of Charles II in 1660.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was badly damaged by the (protectionist) English Navigation Acts of 1660 and 1663 and England's wars with the Dutch Republic, Scotland's major export market.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] An Anglo-Scots Trade Commission was set up in January 1668 but the English had no interest in making concessions, as the Scots had little to offer in return.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In 1669, Charles II revived talks on "political union"; his motives may have been to weaken Scotland's commercial and political links with the Dutch, still seen as an enemy and complete the work of his grandfather James I and VI.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] On the Scottish side, the proposed union received parliamentary support, boosted by the desire to ensure free trade.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Continued opposition meant these negotiations were abandoned by the end of 1669.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Convention of the Estates issued an address to William and Mary "as both kingdomes are united in one head and soveraigne so they may become one body pollitick, one nation to be represented in one parliament", reserving "our church government, as it shall be established at the tyme of the union".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] William and Mary were supportive of the idea but it was opposed both by the Presbyterian majority in Scotland and the English Parliament.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Episcopacy in Scotland was abolished in 1690, alienating a significant part of the political class; it was this element that later formed the bedrock of opposition to Union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The 1690s were a time of economic hardship in Europe as a whole and Scotland in particular, a period now known as the Seven ill years which led to strained relations with England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In 1698, the Company of Scotland Trading to Africa and the Indies received a charter to raise capital through public subscription.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Company invested in the Darién scheme, an ambitious plan funded almost entirely by Scottish investors to build a colony on the Isthmus of Panama for trade with East Asia.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The scheme was a disaster; the losses of over £150,000 severely impacted the Scottish commercial system.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The International Treaty, and English and Scots acts of ratification of Union may be seen within a wider European context of increasing state centralisation during the late 17th and early 18th centuries, including the monarchies of France, Sweden, Denmark-Norway and Spain.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] While there were exceptions, such as the Dutch Republic or the Republic of Venice, the trend was clear.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The dangers of the monarch using one parliament against the other first became apparent in 1647 and 1651.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It resurfaced during the 1679 to 1681 Exclusion Crisis, caused by English resistance to the Catholic prince James (later James II of England, James VII of Scots) succeeding his brother Charles II.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It then went beyond ensuring James's succession to the Scots throne by explicitly stating the aim was to make his exclusion from the English throne impossible without "the fatall and dreadfull consequences of a civil war".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The issue reappeared during the 1688 Dutch invasion and *coup d'etat* (subsequently entitled as "the Glorious Revolution").
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The English Convention Parliament generally supported replacing James with his Protestant daughter Mary, holding to their "legal fiction" that James, by fleeing to France, had abandoned his English subjects and "abdicated".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] They initially resisted making her Dutch husband William of Orange joint ruler but relented, "fearing the return of James" only when William threatened to take his troops and fleet and return to the Netherlands, and Mary refused to rule without him.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, it became a Constitutional issue.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The fact that King James had not been present in Scotland meant that the question of abdication need not arise.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] On 4 April 1689 a Convention of the Three Estates of Scotland (sister body to the Parliament of Scotland) declared that James "had acted irregularly" by assuming regal power (government) "without ever taking the Coronation Oath required by Scots Law".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Thus, he had "FOREFALTED [forfeited] the Right to the Scots Crown, and the Scots Throne is become vacant".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] "Scots monarchs derived legitimacy from the Convention of the Estates", later declared a Parliament of Scotland, not God, thus ending the principle of divine right of kings.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Conflict over control of the kirk between Presbyterians and Episcopalians and William's position as a fellow Calvinist put him in a much stronger position.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] He originally insisted on retaining Episcopacy, and the Committee of the Articles, an unelected body that controlled what legislation Parliament could debate.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Both would have given the Crown far greater control than in England but he withdrew his demands due to the 1689–1692 Jacobite Rising.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] 2. the Convention of the Estates was a parliament and so parliament could just rewrite it.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Here is the Claim of Right understood and upheld for its secular constitutional provisions quite as much as for its religious provisions.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The English succession was provided for by the English Act of Settlement 1701, which ensured that the monarch of England would be a Protestant member of the House of Hanover.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Until the union of parliaments, the Scottish throne might be inherited by a different successor after Queen Anne, who had said in her first speech to the English parliament that a union was "very necessary".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Act of Security 1704, however, was passed after the English parliament, without consultation with Scotland, had designated Electoress Sophia of Hanover (granddaughter of James I and VI) as Anne's successor, if Anne died childless.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Act of Security granted the Parliament of Scotland, the three Estates, the right to choose a successor and explicitly required a choice different from the English monarch unless the English were to grant free trade and navigation.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Then the Alien Act 1705 was passed in the English parliament, designating Scots in England as "foreign nationals" and blocking about half of all Scottish trade by boycotting exports to England or its colonies, unless Scotland came back to negotiate a Union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] To encourage a union, "honours, appointments, pensions and even arrears of pay and other expenses were distributed to clinch support from Scottish peers and MPs".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was severely impacted by privateers during the 1688–1697 Nine Years' War and the 1701 War of the Spanish Succession, with the Royal Navy focusing on protecting English ships.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] This compounded the economic pressure caused by the Darien scheme, and the seven ill years of the 1690s, when 5–15% of the population died of starvation.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament was promised financial assistance, protection for its maritime trade, and an end to economic restrictions on trade with England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The votes of the Court party, influenced by Queen Anne's favourite, James Douglas, 2nd Duke of Queensberry, combined with the majority of the Squadrone Volante, were sufficient to ensure passage of the treaty.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The role played by bribery has long been debated. £20,000 was distributed by David Boyle, 1st Earl of Glasgow, of which 60% went to the Duke of Queensberry, the Queen's Commissioner in Parliament.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, John Campbell, 2nd Duke of Argyll was given an English dukedom.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Professor Sir Tom Devine agreed that promises of "favours, sinecures, pensions, offices and straightforward cash bribes became indispensable to secure government majorities".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] As for representation going forwards, Scotland was, in the new united parliament, only to get 45 MPs, one more than Cornwall, and only 16 (unelected) peers in the House of Lords.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] There were mixed opinions in Scotland about the prospect of a union with England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Sir George Lockhart of Carnwath, the only Scottish negotiator to oppose Union, noted "the whole nation appears against (it)".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Another negotiator, Sir John Clerk of Penicuik, who was an ardent Unionist, observed it was "contrary to the inclinations of at least three-fourths of the Kingdom".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] As the seat of the Scottish Parliament, demonstrators in Edinburgh feared the impact of its loss on the local economy.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Elsewhere, there was widespread concern about the independence of the kirk, and possible tax rises.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Virtually all of the print discourses of 1699–1706 spoke against incorporating union, creating the conditions for widespread rejection of the treaty in 1706 and 1707.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In the wake of unionist proselytising in the autumn of 1706 and early 1707, many Scots were undecided about the prospect of a union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Rather, there was considerably more support in Scotland for a federal union with England than an incorporative one, similar to the devolved Scottish parliament that would be established within Britain nearly three centuries later.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] As the treaty passed through the Parliament of Scotland, opposition was voiced by petitions from shires, burghs, presbyteries and parishes.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] According to Christopher Whatley, however, calls for a union with England began in Scotland itself in the 1690s for the purpose of safeguarding the law, line of succession, and to improve the economy.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Ireland, though a kingdom under the same crown, was not included in the union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It remained a separate kingdom, unrepresented in Parliament, and was legally subordinate to Great Britain until the Renunciation Act 1783.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In July 1707 each House of the Parliament of Ireland passed a congratulatory address to Queen Anne, praying that "May God put it in your royal heart to add greater strength and lustre to your crown, by a still more comprehensive Union".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The British government did not respond to the invitation and an equal union between Great Britain and Ireland was out of consideration until the 1790s.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The union with Ireland finally came about on 1 January 1801.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Deeper political integration had been a key policy of Queen Anne from the time she acceded to the throne in 1702.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Under the aegis of the Queen and her ministers in both kingdoms, the parliaments of England and Scotland (the **Act for a Treaty with England 1705**) agreed to participate in fresh negotiations for a union treaty in 1705.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Both countries appointed 31 commissioners to conduct the negotiations.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Most of the Scottish commissioners favoured union, and about half were government ministers and other officials.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] At the head of the list was the Duke of Queensberry, and the Lord Chancellor of Scotland, the Earl of Seafield.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The English commissioners included the Lord High Treasurer, Sidney Godolphin, 1st Earl of Godolphin, the Lord Keeper of the Great Seal, William Cowper, Baron Cowper, and a large number of Whigs who supported union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Tories were not in favour of union and only one was represented among the commissioners.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Negotiations between the English and Scottish commissioners took place between 16 April and 22 July 1706 at the Cockpit in London.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Each side had its own particular concerns.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] After negotiations ended in July 1706, the acts had to be ratified by both Parliaments.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, about 100 of the 227 members of the Parliament of Scotland were supportive of the Court Party.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] For extra votes the pro-court side could rely on about 25 members of the Squadrone Volante, led by the James Graham, 4th Marquess of Montrose and John Ker, 1st Duke of Roxburghe.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Court party enjoyed significant funding from England and the Treasury and included many who had accumulated debts following the Darien Disaster.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The act ratifying the Treaty of Union was finally carried in the Parliament of Scotland by 110 votes to 69 on 16 January 1707, with a number of key amendments.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] News of the ratification and of the amendments was received in Westminster, where the Act was passed quickly through both Houses and received the royal assent on 6 March.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Though the English Act was later in date, it bore the year '1706' while Scotland's was '1707', as the legal year in England began only on 25 March.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, the Duke of Queensberry was largely responsible for the successful passage of the Union act by the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, he was greeted by stones and eggs but in England he was cheered for his action.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] He had personally received around half of the funding awarded by the Westminster Treasury.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In April 1707, he travelled to London to attend celebrations at the royal court, and was greeted by groups of noblemen and gentry lined along the road.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] From Barnet, the route was lined with crowds of cheering people, and once he reached London a huge crowd had formed.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] On 17 April, the Duke was gratefully received by the Queen at Kensington Palace and the Acts came into effect on 1 May 1707.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] A day of thanksgiving was declared in England and Ireland but not in Scotland, where the bells of St Giles rang out the tune of *"why should I be so sad on my wedding day"*.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Treaty of Union, agreed between representatives of the Parliament of England and the Parliament of Scotland in 1706, consisted of 25 articles, 15 of which were economic in nature.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In Scotland, each article was voted on separately and several clauses in articles were delegated to specialised subcommittees.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Article 1 of the treaty was based on the political principle of an incorporating union and this was secured by a majority of 116 votes to 83 on 4 November 1706.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] To minimise the opposition of the Church of Scotland, an Act was also passed to secure the Presbyterian establishment of the Church, after which the Church stopped its open opposition, although hostility remained at lower levels of the clergy.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The treaty as a whole was finally ratified on 16 January 1707 by a majority of 110 votes to 69.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The two Acts incorporated provisions for Scotland to send representative peers from the Peerage of Scotland to sit in the House of Lords.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It guaranteed that the Church of Scotland would remain the established church in Scotland, that the Court of Session would "remain in all time coming within Scotland", and that Scots law would "remain in the same force as before".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Other provisions included the restatement of the Act of Settlement 1701 and the ban on Roman Catholics from taking the throne.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] It also created a customs union and monetary union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Act provided that any "laws and statutes" that were "contrary to or inconsistent with the terms" of the Act would "cease and become void".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament also passed the Protestant Religion and Presbyterian Church Act 1707 guaranteeing the status of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The English Parliament passed a similar Act, 6 Ann. c.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] 40—later named the Union with Scotland (Amendment) Act 1707—united the Privy Council of England and Privy Council of Scotland and decentralised Scottish administration by appointing justices of the peace in each shire to carry out administration.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In effect it took the day-to-day government of Scotland out of the hands of politicians and into those of the College of Justice.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] On 18 December 1707 the Act for better Securing the Duties of East India Goods was passed which extended the monopoly of the East India Company to Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In the year following the Union, the Treason Act 1708 abolished the Scottish law of treason and extended the corresponding English law across Great Britain.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Clark, gaining "freedom of trade with England and the colonies" as well as "a great expansion of markets".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The agreement guaranteed the permanent status of the Presbyterian church in Scotland, and the separate system of laws and courts in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] However, the Scottish economy was lagging behind not only from the impact of wars, but also because of chronic deflation and industrial underdevelopment.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland remained a predominantly agrarian society, and the lack of manpower caused by previous conflicts contributed to an underwhelming agricultural output, which intermittently escalated into local food shortages or famines.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In turn, the overreliance of Scottish landowners on foreign goods led to a deficit of financial capital, as gold and silver were exported overseas and deflation occurred.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish Parliament attempted to combat the issue by attracting foreign investment; duty on ship building materials was lifted, taxes on new manufacturing stocks were cut, and customs on textile and linen goods were removed.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland grew increasingly dependent on its linen industry, which became the biggest source of employment after agriculture and constituted one-third of Scottish industry.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Continental linen industries could outcompete Scotland, and protectionist tariffs implemented by Scotland led to tariff wars as European countries closed their markets to Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In this situation, England became the largest foreign market for Scottish linen; however, while the tariffs in place shielded Scotland from the much larger English industry, England also retaliated against them.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] This forced Scotland to seek economic alternatives.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] At the time, trade with colonies was rapidly growing in importance in Europe, and trade with colonies was very attractive to Scotland, given its pastoral economy.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] American colonies had a high demand of agricultural goods such as leather skins of goats and sheep, which would have provided Scotland a valuable source of income.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Search for colonial trade, along with the frustration caused by economic and political rivalry with England, led to the Darien scheme – an unsuccessful attempt to establish a Scottish colony in the Gulf of Darién.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The failure of the Darien scheme led to a financial crisis in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The high cost of its project exacerbated the deflation in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Bank of Scotland had dangerously low reserves, and in early 1700s a run on the bank occurred, along with temporary suspension of business.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, the Scottish bank managed to stay solvent, although the persisting deflation and low reserves largely contributed to the feeling of Scottish economy being in a precarious position.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Economist Aida Ramos argues that the Darien scheme could have succeeded if it was to receive support from either England or Spain, and that it lacked the capability to create a threat to England or its interests.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] According to Ramos, the English intervention against the scheme was to meet the expansionary aims of England, as to ensure both its colonial dominance as well as the annexation of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] By 1703, the Scottish government was highly disillusioned with the union, and many believed that the only way to let the Scottish economy flourish was to separate from England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Scotland would try to establish further autonomy from England with the Act of Security 1704, which provoked a retaliation from England – Scottish ministers were bribed, and Alien Act 1705 was passed.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] According to the Alien Act, unless Scotland appointed commissioners to negotiate for union by Christmas, every Scot in England would be treated as an alien, leading to the confiscation of their English estates.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Additionally, Scottish wares were to be banned from England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The Scottish economy was now facing a crisis, and the parliament was polarised into pro-union and anti-union factions, with the former led by Daniel Defoe.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] The unionists stressed how important trade with England is to the Scottish economy, and seen trade with continental Europe as not beneficial.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the Scottish economy could survive by trading with England, and sanctions that would result from the Alien Act would collapse the economy.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] For Defoe, joining the union would not only prevent the Alien Act, but also remove additional limitations and regulations and lead Scotland to prosperity.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Anti-unionists questioned the English goodwill and criticised the unionist faction for submitting to the English blackmail.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that Scotland could make a recovery by trading with the Netherlands, Spain and Norway, allowing Scotland to diversify its own industries as well.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] They argued that the union would make Scotland unable to conduct independent trade policy, meaning that any possibility to remove the flaws in Scottish economy would be gone forever, which would turn Scotland into a "mere satellite of the richer kingdom".
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Ultimately, Scottish ministers voted in favour of the union, despite the lack of public support, with the overwhelming majority of the Scottish population at the time protesting vociferously against any union with England.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Many Scots considered themselves to have been betrayed by their own elites, and that the union bill was able to pass only thanks to English bribery.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] In the first few decades after the union, England did not end up becoming the main trading partner of Scotland, as other European powers became the primary source of imported goods for Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] For at least the first 40 years after the union, Scotland persisted in its traditional trade patterns, and the economic situation of Scotland was not as dire as that described in the months leading up to the Acts of Union.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] Christopher Whatley writes, however, that by 1799, it was reported that the union of Scotland with England had not only benefitted the Scottish economy, but promoted a "commercial prosperity" unknown to any people.
[src:college-of-justice/acts-of-union-1707] A commemorative two-pound coin was issued to mark the tercentennial—300th anniversary—of the Union, which occurred two days before the Scottish Parliament general election on 3 May 2007.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The **College of Justice** (Scottish Gaelic: *Colaiste a' Cheartais*) includes the **Supreme Courts of Scotland**, and its associated bodies.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The constituent bodies of the national supreme courts are the Court of Session, the High Court of Justiciary, the Office of the Accountant of Court, and the Auditor of the Court of Session.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Its associated bodies are the Faculty of Advocates, the Society of Writers to His Majesty's Signet and the Society of Solicitors in the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The college is headed by the Lord President of the Court of Session, who also holds the title of Lord Justice General in relation to the High Court of Justiciary, and judges of the Court of Session and High Court are titled Senators of the College of Justice.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The college was founded in 1532 by King James V following a bull issued by Pope Clement VII on 15 September 1531.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] It provided for 10,000 gold ducats to be contributed by the Scottish bishoprics and monastic institutions for the maintenance of its members, one half of whom would be members of the "ecclesiastical dignity".
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Parliament of Scotland passed the **College of Justice Act 1532** (c.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] 2 (S)) on 17 May 1532 authorising the creation of the college with 14 members, half spiritual, half temporal, plus a president and the Lord Chancellor.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The college convened for the first time on 27 May 1532, in the royal presence.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Supplementing the 14 ordinary lords, who were called senators, were an indefinite number of supernumerary judges called extraordinary lords.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The college at its foundation dealt with underdeveloped civil law.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] It did not dispense justice in criminal matters as that was an area of the law reserved to the king's justice, through the justiciars (hence the High Court of the Justiciary), the Barony Courts and the Commission of Justiciary.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court of Justiciary was only incorporated into the College of Justice in 1672.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Initially, there was little legal literature.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Acts of the Parliament of Scotland and the books of the Old Law as well as Roman Law and canon law texts were about all to which the pursuer and defender could refer.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] It was only after the establishment of the court that this situation improved, with judges noting their decisions in books of practicks.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Treaty of Union 1707 with England preserved the Scottish Legal System.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Court of Session is the highest national court of Scotland in relation to civil cases.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The court was established in 1532 to take on the judicial functions of the royal council.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Its jurisdiction overlapped with other royal, state and church courts but as those were disbanded, the role of the Court of Session ascended.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Acts of Union establishing the United Kingdom provided that the court will "remain in all time coming".
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Cases at first instance are heard in the Outer House by a single judge.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Inner House hears appeals from the Outer House and all other courts and tribunals in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Only Scottish advocates and solicitor-advocates may argue cases before the court.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Court of Session has sat at Parliament House since 1707.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service and the Principal Clerk administers the court and judges.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The creation of the court was part of wider efforts to improve and reform access to justice in Scottish society.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] By 1153, the local feudal courts had been established.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Depending on the part of Scotland where the cause originated, justice might also be available from the local baron or lord of regality, sitting with the king's authority.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Parties often found these courts ineffectual.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Appeal of the decisions of local courts lay to the king and the Lords of Council, sitting together as the King's Council, or the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The burden on these bodies of hearing appeals led to a growing effort to divest their judicial functions.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court of Justiciary is the supreme criminal court in Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court is both a trial court and a court of appeal.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] As a trial court, the High Court sits on circuit at Parliament House or in the adjacent former Sheriff Court building in the Old Town in Edinburgh, or in dedicated buildings in Glasgow and Aberdeen.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court sometimes sits in various smaller towns in Scotland, where it uses the local sheriff court building.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] As an appeal court, the High Court sits only in Edinburgh.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] On one occasion the High Court of Justiciary sat outside Scotland, at Zeist in the Netherlands during the Pan Am Flight 103 bombing trial, as the Scottish Court in the Netherlands.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] At Zeist the High Court sat both as a trial court, and an appeal court for the initial appeal by Abdelbaset al-Megrahi.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court will hear appeals from the sheriff courts of Scotland where the trial was under solemn proceedings; the High Court will also hear referrals on points of law from the Sheriff Appeal Court, and from summary proceedings in the sheriff courts and justice of the peace courts.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Cases can be remitted to the High Court by the sheriff courts after conviction for sentencing, where a sheriff believes that their sentencing powers are inadequate.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The High Court can impose a life sentence but the sheriff has a limit of five years sentencing; both can issue an unlimited fine.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The origins derive from the Justiciar and College of Justice, as well as from the medieval royal courts and barony courts.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The medieval Justiciar (royal judge) took its name from the justices who originally travelled around Scotland hearing cases on circuit or 'ayre'.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] From 1524, the Justiciar or a depute was required to have a "permanent base" in Edinburgh.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The King of Scots sometimes sat in judgment of cases in the early King's Court, and it appears that appeals could be taken from the King's Court to the Parliament of Scotland in civil cases but not in criminal ones.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] In 1532 the College of Justice was founded, separating civil and criminal jurisdiction between two distinct courts.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The King's Court was, however, normally the responsibility of the Justiciar.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Justiciar normally appointed several deputes to assist in the administration of justice, and to preside in his absence.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] A legally qualified clerk advised the Justiciar and his deputes as they were generally noblemen and often not legally qualified.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] This clerk prepared all the indictments and was keeper of the records.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Eventually the influence of the clerk increased until the clerk gained both a vote in the court, and a seat on the bench as the Justice-Clerk.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Office of the Accountant of Court is a public body which is a constituent part of the Supreme Courts of Scotland.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Accountant of Court is administered by the Scottish Courts and Tribunals Service.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Accountant of Court's Office formerly dealt with guardianship cases in respect of adults with incapacity.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] However, following the introduction of the Adults with Incapacity (Scotland) Act 2000 by the Scottish Parliament, these cases were transferred to the new Office of the Public Guardian (Scotland).
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Based in Falkirk, the office of **Accountant of Court**, also known as the **Accountant of the Court of Session** (see Court of Session), was established by the Judicial Factors Act 1849, and their role was further defined by the Children (Scotland) Act 1995.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Accountant of Court is responsible for ensuring that those appointed by the Courts as Judicial Factor in terms of the Judicial Factors Act 1849 manage the estates in their charge properly.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Accountant of Court will generally superintend the actions of a Judicial Factor and provide them with the necessary guidance and direction required progress a case.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] In addition the Accountant of Court is also responsible for investigating any concerns or complaints that are raised against a Judicial Factor.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Accountant of Court is also responsible for supervising Enforcement Administrators appointed by the Courts to recover assets confiscated in terms of the Proceeds of Crime (Scotland) Act 1995.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Senators of the College of Justice are judges of the College of Justice, with three types different types of senator – Lords of Session (judges of the Court of Session); Lords Commissioners of Justiciary (judges of the High Court of Justiciary); and the Chairman of the Scottish Land Court.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] Whilst the High Court and Court of Session historically maintained separate judiciary, these are now identical, and the term *senator* is almost exclusively used in referring to the judges of these courts.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] On occasions, temporary judges may be appointed to sit in the Supreme Courts of Scotland in order to carry out the same work as permanent senators but will carry out their duties on a part-time basis, and as a result, are referred to as "Judge" rather than Lord or Lady.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The Court of Session has in place "special provisions" allowing it to deal with commercial actions which would ensure that specialist judges handle cases quickly and flexibly.
[src:college-of-justice/college-of-justice] The current commercial judges are Lord Tyre, Lord Clark, Lord Braid and Lord Ericht.
